  "Only studying the Sun": "",
  "Returning humans to the Moon, establishing sustainable presence, and preparing for Mars": "",
  "Only building a space station": "",
  "NASA's Artemis program is a multi-phase initiative designed to return astronauts to the lunar surface, build a sustainable presence there, and use the Moon as a stepping stone for eventual crewed missions to Mars.": "",
  "A Mars transit using a Hohmann transfer orbit takes approximately:": "",
  "1 month, particularly": "",
  "1 week, particularly regardin": "",
  "6 to 9 months depending on trajectory": "",
  "5 years, particularly": "",
  "Using a minimum-energy Hohmann transfer orbit, a spacecraft traveling from Earth to Mars takes roughly 6 to 9 months, depending on the specific alignment of the two planets at the time of launch.": "",
  "SpaceX's Starship is designed to be:": "",
  "Fully reusable in both stages, dramatically reducing launch costs": "",
  "Only for cargo delivery to LEO": "",
  "Expendable like traditional rockets": "",
  "A single-use deep space probe": "",
  "SpaceX's Starship system is designed for full reusability of both the Super Heavy booster and the Starship upper stage, which would dramatically lower per-launch costs and enable frequent flights to the Moon, Mars, and beyond.": "",
  "Lunar south pole ice deposits are valuable because:": "",
  "They are visually beautiful from orbit": "",
  "They contain deposits of gold and diamonds": "",
  "They prove that the Moon once had oceans": "",
  "Water ice can be used for drinking, oxygen production, and rocket fuel": "",
  "Water ice trapped in permanently shadowed craters at the lunar south pole can be extracted and split into hydrogen and oxygen through electrolysis, providing drinking water, breathable oxygen, and hydrogen/oxygen rocket propellant for in-situ resource utilization (ISRU).": "",
  "The NASA Space Launch System (SLS) is:": "",
  "NASA's super heavy-lift rocket designed for Artemis Moon missions": "",
  "A commercial rocket built by SpaceX": "",
  "A cancelled program from the 1990s": "",
